Part 2
The de Casteljau algorithm is a recursive method to evaluate Bezier curves at a given parameter
t . This algorithm can be extended to Bezier surfaces by applying it in two dimensions, using two
parameters u and v .
For Bezier surfaces, which are defined by a grid of control points, the algorithm works as
follows: Apply de Casteljau in one direction: Treat each row of control points as defining a
Bezier curve. Apply the de Casteljau algorithm to each row with the parameter u to find the
intermediate control points along each row. This results in a new set of control points that form a
"cross-section" of the surface. Then apply de Casteljau in the orthogonal direction: use the new
set of control points obtained from the first step as control points of Bezier curves running in the
orthogonal direction. Apply the de Casteljau algorithm to these points with the parameter v to
evaluate the point on the surface at.
For our implementation, we implement the evaluateStep method for a Bezier surface by
computing the intermediate control points for a given parameter t . This will be similar to the
evaluateStep method for Bezier curves, but will work with Vector3D points instead of Vector2D.
And we then Implement the evaluate1D method to apply the de Casteljau algorithm recursively,
using the evaluateStep method until we obtain a single point from a 1D Bezier curve. Finally, in
the evaluate method, we use the evaluate1D method twice: once for all rows with parameter u to
compute the new set of control points, and then again for these resulting points with parameter v
to find the final point on the surface.

Part 3
In our implementation, we initialize Normal Accumulator, which we begin by initializing a
Vector3D object to act as an accumulator for the area-weighted normals and then iterate over all
faces incident to the vertex.
Then we calculate face normal by taking the cross product of two edges of the face. Since the
cross product's magnitude is proportional to the parallelogram's area formed by the two vectors,
and the triangle is half of this, the resulting vector is already area-weighted. Once all incident
faces have been processed, we normalize the accumulated normal to turn it into a unit vector.

Part 4
The flipEdge implementation follows these steps:
Starts by checking if the edge e0 is a boundary edge. If so, the function returns immediately, as
flipping a boundary edge is now allowed.
Gathers the halfedges, vertices, edges, and faces that are involved in the flip operation.
Uses the setNeighbors method to reassign the next, twin, vertex, edge, and face points of
the halfedges involved in the two triangles adjacent to the edge being flipped.
Halfedges:
h0 and h3 are the two halfedges of the edge being flipped ( e0 ). Their vertex pointers are updated
to point to the vertices that will be connected by the new edge ( v3 and v2 respectively).
h1 , h2 , h4 , and h5 have their next pointers updated to point to the next halfedge in their
respective faces after the flip.
h6 , h7 , h8 , and h9 remain connected to their current faces but their twin pointers are updated to
reflect the new connections.
Vertices:
v0 , v1 , v2 , and v3 now have their halfedge pointers set to one of the halfedges emanating from
them after the flip.
Edges:
e0 is the flipped edge and it keeps one of its halfedges ( h0 ).
The other edges e1 , e2 , e3 , and e4 are not directly affected by the flip but their halfedge pointers
are updated to maintain consistency.
Faces:
f0 and f1 have their halfedge pointers updated to point to one of the halfedges on their boundaries
after the flip.
After reassigning all the pointers, the function returns e0 , which now represents the flipped edge.
This reassignment ensures that all the elements in the mesh remain consistently connected after
the edge flip operation. It's important that all pointers are updated correctly to preserve the
meshs integrity, as any mistake in reassignment can corrupt the data structure and cause issues
with future operations on the mesh.

Part 5
The general logic of splitting edges follows these steps:
Creating a new vertex v4 along the edge e0 .
Creating new half-edges to maintain the structure of the half-edge mesh.
Creating new edges and faces as necessary.
Reassigning the next , twin , vertex , edge , and face pointers to reflect the updated mesh topology.

Part 6:
We first iterate through all vertices in the mesh and calculated the weighted neighboring vertice
positions, and then we following the equation (1 - n * u) * original_position + u *
original_neighbor_position_sum to find the updated positions for each vertice. Then we update
the new positions again with regard to the edges by iterating through all edges and determine
whether they are part of the boundary. If not, we use the 3/8 * (A + B) + 1/8 * (C + D) equation
to calculate the new positions. Then we iterate through all edges in the copied edge list and split
all edges. Then we flip edges that connect only new and old vertices (blue edges). Finally we
update the positions of all vertices.
